WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.570 --> 00:00:05.700
MODERATOR: Thanks for joining
us today to close out our Earth

00:00:05.700 --> 00:00:09.535
Week with Matt Grocoff,
our special guest.

00:00:09.535 --> 00:00:12.290
Matt and I actually
met via a tour

00:00:12.290 --> 00:00:16.480
of his home, which
is kind of weird.

00:00:16.480 --> 00:00:21.210
But he has America's oldest
and Michigan's first net zero

00:00:21.210 --> 00:00:22.510
energy home.

00:00:22.510 --> 00:00:24.080
And articles about
this home have

00:00:24.080 --> 00:00:27.300
been featured in "USA
Today" and "The Atlantic"

00:00:27.300 --> 00:00:29.930
and numerous other publications.

00:00:29.930 --> 00:00:34.420
Matt is the founding principal
of THRIVE Net Zero Energy

00:00:34.420 --> 00:00:37.610
Consulting Collaborative
and the co-founder

00:00:37.610 --> 00:00:39.720
of Mission Zero Fest.

00:00:39.720 --> 00:00:41.710
And he is an advocate
and thought leader

00:00:41.710 --> 00:00:45.767
on net zero energy building
and restorative design.

00:00:45.767 --> 00:00:47.400
So Matt, thanks for being here.

00:00:49.696 --> 00:00:51.904
MATT GROCOFF: This is great,
because this is actually

00:00:51.904 --> 00:00:54.010
the first talk that
I've gotten to do here.

00:00:54.010 --> 00:00:55.853
Happy first day of spring.

00:00:55.853 --> 00:00:58.840
It comes a little bit
later here in Michigan.

00:00:58.840 --> 00:01:03.040
But speaking of spring and
temperature and comfort

00:01:03.040 --> 00:01:06.020
and everything else, we don't
measure our lives in stuff,

00:01:06.020 --> 00:01:06.520
right?

00:01:06.520 --> 00:01:09.980
We measure our lives
in love, in happiness.

00:01:09.980 --> 00:01:13.980
But comfort is that
tool that we use,

00:01:13.980 --> 00:01:15.900
that zone that we
want to put ourselves

00:01:15.900 --> 00:01:20.810
into in order to provide us that
space for love and happiness

00:01:20.810 --> 00:01:22.910
and joy and
friendship and family,

00:01:22.910 --> 00:01:24.410
and all those other
wonderful things

00:01:24.410 --> 00:01:26.040
that we do measure our lives in.

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:28.013
But about 10,000 years
ago was the first time

00:01:28.013 --> 00:01:30.900
it became off of the
savanna, out from, literally

00:01:30.900 --> 00:01:32.589
from the treetops,
out of caves, places

00:01:32.589 --> 00:01:34.130
where we were trying
to find shelter,

00:01:34.130 --> 00:01:36.730
and started building our own
shelter from other things.

00:01:36.730 --> 00:01:38.937
Only for about 10,000 years.

00:01:38.937 --> 00:01:40.770
So originally, we went
around the camp fires

00:01:40.770 --> 00:01:42.376
and we stayed warm.

00:01:42.376 --> 00:01:44.500
They wouldn't even sleep
8 hours through the night.

00:01:44.500 --> 00:01:46.666
They would wake up in the
middle of the night, dance

00:01:46.666 --> 00:01:48.390
around the fire to
entertain themselves.

00:01:48.390 --> 00:01:50.590
Now we've really tried
to capitalize ourselves

00:01:50.590 --> 00:01:52.799
with comfort as much
as we possibly can.

00:01:52.799 --> 00:01:55.090
So we've got ourselves now
we're entertaining ourselves

00:01:55.090 --> 00:01:58.105
with the Harlem shake,
with Gangnam style.

00:01:58.105 --> 00:02:01.435
We have-- originally, we're
pooping out by the tree and now

00:02:01.435 --> 00:02:02.720
in the outhouse.

00:02:02.720 --> 00:02:05.560
Then we brought in
the chamber pot.

00:02:05.560 --> 00:02:07.713
But that obviously
wasn't the real way

00:02:07.713 --> 00:02:09.563
to go, so we started
using indoor toilets,

00:02:09.563 --> 00:02:10.229
indoor plumbing.

00:02:10.229 --> 00:02:12.070
So we have these things
that are flushing

00:02:12.070 --> 00:02:14.230
15 gallons of fresh
water down the drain.

00:02:14.230 --> 00:02:16.070
But that's still
not enough comfort.

00:02:16.070 --> 00:02:18.510
Because if you're the
toilet trained cat owner,

00:02:18.510 --> 00:02:21.030
you've got to have one
for your cat, as well.

00:02:21.030 --> 00:02:23.023
Now for you
[INAUDIBLE] out there,

00:02:23.023 --> 00:02:25.388
this is the ultimate convenience
for the toilet trained

00:02:25.388 --> 00:02:26.674
cat owner.

00:02:26.674 --> 00:02:29.090
I'm assuming they're talking
about the cat, not the owner.

00:02:29.090 --> 00:02:30.870
But here, if you've
got your own elephant,

00:02:30.870 --> 00:02:32.670
you gotta have a
toilet for that, too.

00:02:32.670 --> 00:02:34.130
It's not enough just
for the indoor animals.

00:02:34.130 --> 00:02:35.780
We can't serve our
own coffee anymore

00:02:35.780 --> 00:02:37.350
or cut our own hot dogs.

00:02:37.350 --> 00:02:38.880
This one here is
my own favorite.

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:42.240
This is really the symbol
of the end of time,

00:02:42.240 --> 00:02:43.520
as far as I'm concerned.

00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:47.465
This is the proof of the over
capitalization of comfort.

00:02:47.465 --> 00:02:48.590
I can't make this stuff up.

00:02:48.590 --> 00:02:49.240
It's real.

00:02:49.240 --> 00:02:50.960
You can look this up on Amazon.

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:58.640
There's over 2,000 reviews of
this product, the Hutzler 571B.

00:02:58.640 --> 00:03:01.420
I think B is for banana,
but I'm not sure.

00:03:01.420 --> 00:03:02.920
$2.48 on Amazon.

00:03:02.920 --> 00:03:03.740
And these are real.

00:03:03.740 --> 00:03:04.490
These are reviews.

00:03:04.490 --> 00:03:06.090
Here's one from Miss Toledo.

00:03:06.090 --> 00:03:09.890
She raves, "this
saved my marriage.

00:03:09.890 --> 00:03:12.530
What can I say about the
571B that hasn't already

00:03:12.530 --> 00:03:17.920
been said about the wheel,
penicillin or the iPhone?"

00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:20.800
And now we're starting see
the consequences of some

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:23.702
of this, what I call the over
capitalization of comfort.

00:03:23.702 --> 00:03:25.430
This is the number 350.

00:03:25.430 --> 00:03:28.270
This is parts per
million of carbon dioxide

00:03:28.270 --> 00:03:30.158
in our atmosphere.

00:03:30.158 --> 00:03:33.620
This is what Bill McKibben
calls the most important number

00:03:33.620 --> 00:03:35.986
in the world that
everybody should know.

00:03:35.986 --> 00:03:38.940
And the reason he says that is
because James Hansen determined

00:03:38.940 --> 00:03:42.200
that above this number, parts
per million in the atmosphere,

00:03:42.200 --> 00:03:46.620
if we keep it above this
level for a significant period

00:03:46.620 --> 00:03:52.230
of time, we can't sustain
the biosphere to which humans

00:03:52.230 --> 00:03:55.590
have adapted over
these 10,000 years.

00:03:55.590 --> 00:03:59.740
We can't sustain wildlife or
any of the living things that

00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:02.052
adapted to this kind of climate.

00:04:02.052 --> 00:04:03.510
But this is the
number that I think

00:04:03.510 --> 00:04:06.692
is the most important
number, zero.

00:04:06.692 --> 00:04:09.394
That's zero carbon pollution
going up into the atmosphere.

00:04:09.394 --> 00:04:11.810
Because this is the number
that we can impact in our daily

00:04:11.810 --> 00:04:12.590
lives every day.

00:04:12.590 --> 00:04:14.675
This is the number we
can impact at home.

00:04:14.675 --> 00:04:16.430
350 is for the scientists.

00:04:16.430 --> 00:04:19.459
Zero carbon emissions
out of your office place,

00:04:19.459 --> 00:04:22.650
from your automobiles,
from your homes,

00:04:22.650 --> 00:04:25.130
completely decarbonizing
our economy down

00:04:25.130 --> 00:04:28.336
to zero carbon going up
into the atmosphere, that's

00:04:28.336 --> 00:04:29.961
our ultimate goal,
and that's something

00:04:29.961 --> 00:04:32.500
that we can impact
every single day.

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:34.710
James Hansen gave
us that number, 350.

00:04:34.710 --> 00:04:38.400
He says that stabilizing
atmospheric CO2 and climate

00:04:38.400 --> 00:04:42.180
requires that CO2
emissions approach zero.

00:04:42.180 --> 00:04:45.950
Now this is from a
scientific paper.

00:04:45.950 --> 00:04:48.620
They didn't say
it's a suggestion,

00:04:48.620 --> 00:04:51.110
they said it's a requirement.

00:04:51.110 --> 00:04:55.420
It's a whole lot easier to
change the way we use energy

00:04:55.420 --> 00:04:57.600
than it is to change
the laws of physics.

00:04:57.600 --> 00:04:59.970
It is a physical
law, a requirement

00:04:59.970 --> 00:05:03.870
that we have to get to
zero carbon emissions.

00:05:03.870 --> 00:05:05.350
So this is our house.

00:05:05.350 --> 00:05:08.493
Over here on the old
West Side in Ann Arbor.

00:05:08.493 --> 00:05:12.922
This picture was taken
probably in about 1912.

00:05:12.922 --> 00:05:15.986
Our house was built in 1901.

00:05:15.986 --> 00:05:18.110
Since we've done a little
bit of work to the house,

00:05:18.110 --> 00:05:19.050
it's gotten a lot of attention.

00:05:19.050 --> 00:05:20.170
We were in USA Today.

00:05:20.170 --> 00:05:23.650
It was called one of the
top greenhouses of 2010.

00:05:23.650 --> 00:05:26.160
The Atlantic called it
sustainable perfection.

00:05:26.160 --> 00:05:28.400
I'm getting calls from
around the country for people

00:05:28.400 --> 00:05:30.252
to-- they call me the
zero energy master.

00:05:30.252 --> 00:05:31.335
It sounds very dominating.

00:05:31.335 --> 00:05:33.790
I kind of like the term.

00:05:33.790 --> 00:05:35.969
And so I spoke at the World
Renewable Energy Forum

00:05:35.969 --> 00:05:38.260
at Greenbuild and Living
Futures Conference next month,

00:05:38.260 --> 00:05:39.950
and at Google.

00:05:39.950 --> 00:05:43.430
And people are saying, what
did you do to this house?

00:05:43.430 --> 00:05:45.680
How could you get this
112-year-old house

00:05:45.680 --> 00:05:47.810
to net zero energy?

00:05:47.810 --> 00:05:50.285
And it's a really simple story
that goes back to 2006, when

00:05:50.285 --> 00:05:52.701
my wife and I were thinking
it might be a really good time

00:05:52.701 --> 00:05:53.326
to buy a house.

00:05:53.326 --> 00:05:54.670
And the market is going crazy.

00:05:54.670 --> 00:05:56.545
If we buy a house
now, imagine what

00:05:56.545 --> 00:05:58.662
it's going to be like in 2008.

00:05:58.662 --> 00:05:59.902
[LAUGHTER]

00:05:59.902 --> 00:06:02.360
And then we heard on the radio--
and this was a true story.

00:06:02.360 --> 00:06:03.276
This was the catalyst.

00:06:03.276 --> 00:06:06.000
We heard that Google was
bringing 1,000 new employees

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:07.060
to town.

00:06:07.060 --> 00:06:08.060
And my wife called me.

00:06:08.060 --> 00:06:09.075
She said, did you
just hear on NPR?

00:06:09.075 --> 00:06:10.390
Google is coming to town.

00:06:10.390 --> 00:06:10.900
They're bringing
1,000 employees.

00:06:10.900 --> 00:06:12.005
We've got to buy a house now.

00:06:12.005 --> 00:06:14.005
There's all these people
coming from California.

00:06:14.005 --> 00:06:16.370
They don't know what
houses are worth!

00:06:16.370 --> 00:06:19.116
So this is the house we bought.

00:06:19.116 --> 00:06:22.245
And I'm pointing at the
computer, not at the screen.

00:06:22.245 --> 00:06:23.100
This was the house.

00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:24.721
This was our dream house.

00:06:24.721 --> 00:06:27.299
We went in and buy this thing
on a July afternoon and said,

00:06:27.299 --> 00:06:28.840
that is the house
we want to live in.

00:06:28.840 --> 00:06:30.470
It's got everything
we could ever want.

00:06:30.470 --> 00:06:33.340
It's got plywood front
porch, asbestos siding,

00:06:33.340 --> 00:06:35.700
zero insulation in
the entire house,

00:06:35.700 --> 00:06:39.740
except for a layer of
newspaper dated 1902.

00:06:39.740 --> 00:06:42.460
We had lead paint,
which everybody wants.

00:06:42.460 --> 00:06:46.890
We had no operable windows,
which was really fun.

00:06:46.890 --> 00:06:48.340
Even though they
weren't operable,

00:06:48.340 --> 00:06:50.010
and you can see some
of the little sash

00:06:50.010 --> 00:06:51.722
locks here are missing,
you could still

00:06:51.722 --> 00:06:54.330
stick a spatula or a screwdriver
right through that hole.

00:06:54.330 --> 00:06:56.204
And there was plenty of
air going through it,

00:06:56.204 --> 00:06:58.990
so we weren't worried about
suffocating in the house.

00:06:58.990 --> 00:07:01.750
We had carpet covering
hard pine floors that

00:07:01.750 --> 00:07:04.900
were from trees that were
harvested 112 years ago

00:07:04.900 --> 00:07:06.560
and were probably
growing at the time

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:10.490
Christopher Columbus
sailed for the Americas.

00:07:10.490 --> 00:07:13.150
Certainly worth
putting carpet over.

00:07:13.150 --> 00:07:16.180
This was a refrigerator from
1989 inside the kitchen,

00:07:16.180 --> 00:07:18.710
with the linoleum floors.

00:07:18.710 --> 00:07:20.710
This was the bathroom,
with the toilet

00:07:20.710 --> 00:07:22.900
that flushed 5
gallons every time.

00:07:22.900 --> 00:07:26.340
So we took this much waste and
turned it into this much wast.

00:07:26.340 --> 00:07:28.520
And my favorite part
of that bathroom,

00:07:28.520 --> 00:07:32.917
though, is the pink towel
curtains sewed together.

00:07:32.917 --> 00:07:34.750
This house didn't have
a shower at the time.

00:07:34.750 --> 00:07:36.195
This was the only bath.

00:07:36.195 --> 00:07:38.355
This was one of only two
rooms in the house that

00:07:38.355 --> 00:07:41.080
had running water in it
when we brought in 2006.

00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:43.492
It did have genuine
Formica tile.

00:07:43.492 --> 00:07:45.700
A few times I made the
mistake of saying it was fake.

00:07:45.700 --> 00:07:48.490
But no, it's real Formica.

00:07:48.490 --> 00:07:51.776
The sink was flowing at two
or three gallons a minute,

00:07:51.776 --> 00:07:53.400
two-and-a-half, three
gallons a minute.

00:07:53.400 --> 00:07:55.843
This is the Mueller
Climatrol furnace from 1957.

00:07:55.843 --> 00:07:59.475
A little white tag on there
shows the date of installation

00:07:59.475 --> 00:08:03.170
and some inspections that
were done over the years.

00:08:03.170 --> 00:08:06.200
This thing operated, it
was about 40% efficiency.

00:08:06.200 --> 00:08:10.102
60% of it was just donations
to the utility company.

00:08:10.102 --> 00:08:13.572
And for the privilege of
paying that $350 a month

00:08:13.572 --> 00:08:15.280
to the utility company
to run this thing,

00:08:15.280 --> 00:08:18.710
we got to sleep with two down
comforters, fully clothed

00:08:18.710 --> 00:08:21.359
in sweat pants,
sweatshirts, socks

00:08:21.359 --> 00:08:23.400
and a buckwheat pillow
heated up in the microwave

00:08:23.400 --> 00:08:25.340
and shoved down at
the bottom of the bed.

00:08:25.340 --> 00:08:27.880
Barely, barely
comfortable, at that.

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:33.559
So we wanted to create
a vision for what

00:08:33.559 --> 00:08:34.909
we wanted this house to be.

00:08:34.909 --> 00:08:36.284
Because I was a
little upset when

00:08:36.284 --> 00:08:37.809
my mom came into
the house and she

00:08:37.809 --> 00:08:40.471
didn't just get blown away right
away when she saw the asbestos

00:08:40.471 --> 00:08:41.929
siding and the
carbon on the floor.

00:08:41.929 --> 00:08:43.600
I was like, so,
what do you think?

00:08:43.600 --> 00:08:44.965
Check out our new house.

00:08:44.965 --> 00:08:46.620
Really upset with
my Jewish mother

00:08:46.620 --> 00:08:48.230
and she's like-- what, nothing?

00:08:48.230 --> 00:08:50.188
You're not going to say
a word about the house?

00:08:50.188 --> 00:08:51.586
It'll look nice when it's done.

00:08:51.586 --> 00:08:52.020
What do you mean?

00:08:52.020 --> 00:08:52.645
It's beautiful.

00:08:52.645 --> 00:08:53.543
Look at--

00:08:53.543 --> 00:08:56.024
So we did have a vision.

00:08:56.024 --> 00:08:58.440
Yogi Berra said that if you
don't know where you're going,

00:08:58.440 --> 00:09:00.517
you might not get there.

00:09:00.517 --> 00:09:02.850
And there's a gentleman in
town you might have heard of,

00:09:02.850 --> 00:09:06.914
Ari Weinzweig, who owns
Zimmerman's Deli, a little $45

00:09:06.914 --> 00:09:07.580
million company.

00:09:10.260 --> 00:09:11.580
They talk a lot about vision.

00:09:11.580 --> 00:09:13.520
And he says, vision
is not the how.

00:09:13.520 --> 00:09:16.300
Vision is the what.

00:09:16.300 --> 00:09:19.840
And as Sir Mix-a-Lot once said,
I like big whats and I cannot

00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:20.563
lie.

00:09:20.563 --> 00:09:22.930
You want the biggest what
you can possibly find.

00:09:22.930 --> 00:09:24.737
Then we figure out how to do it.

00:09:24.737 --> 00:09:27.112
And it was one of the Googlers,
either Larry Page or some

00:09:27.112 --> 00:09:29.030
of the other guys who
talks about 10 times

00:09:29.030 --> 00:09:31.425
versus the 10 percent gain.

00:09:31.425 --> 00:09:32.880
So we wanted to go big.

00:09:32.880 --> 00:09:34.880
We wanted to go to
this number here.

00:09:34.880 --> 00:09:39.340
We wanted zero carbon emissions
out of a century old house.

00:09:39.340 --> 00:09:42.550
And having no idea
that it was impossible.

00:09:42.550 --> 00:09:45.160
But that's why we
knew it was possible.

00:09:45.160 --> 00:09:47.930
This guy over here, from
another computer company,

00:09:47.930 --> 00:09:51.785
he was asked, if he had
one wish, what would it be?

00:09:51.785 --> 00:09:53.910
And he didn't say, hey,
I'd pick the next President

00:09:53.910 --> 00:09:56.195
of the United States, or
I'd bring world peace,

00:09:56.195 --> 00:10:00.705
or I would come up with
a vaccine for malaria.

00:10:00.705 --> 00:10:02.680
That's what the Gates
Foundation does.

00:10:02.680 --> 00:10:04.035
He didn't say that.

00:10:04.035 --> 00:10:08.840
He said, instead, that he
would reduce global emissions

00:10:08.840 --> 00:10:11.290
to zero.

00:10:11.290 --> 00:10:13.100
Because we recognized
that if we don't

00:10:13.100 --> 00:10:18.370
get to that goal of
zero carbon emissions,

00:10:18.370 --> 00:10:21.052
there's no use in trying
to cure diseases or elect

00:10:21.052 --> 00:10:23.060
the Presidents.

00:10:23.060 --> 00:10:25.630
And there's a whole bunch
of folks jumping on board.

00:10:25.630 --> 00:10:29.316
This small company out
of Arkansas, [INAUDIBLE]

00:10:29.316 --> 00:10:31.780
out in California,
and the US Army, all

00:10:31.780 --> 00:10:34.420
have these mission
zero goals of getting

00:10:34.420 --> 00:10:37.675
to zero carbon emissions from
their company, and then some.

00:10:37.675 --> 00:10:40.940
Ultimately, they can be
restorative companies.

00:10:40.940 --> 00:10:43.534
So we figured if Walmart could
do it, then we could, too.

00:10:43.534 --> 00:10:45.450
So we hired as cheap as
laborer as we possibly

00:10:45.450 --> 00:10:47.420
could, ourselves.

00:10:47.420 --> 00:10:51.120
And we targeted our
own mission zero,

00:10:51.120 --> 00:10:55.470
making the house 100%
harvesting our own energy,

00:10:55.470 --> 00:10:59.650
harvesting all of our own
water, creating zero waste.

00:10:59.650 --> 00:11:01.465
And then not only
eliminating the harm

00:11:01.465 --> 00:11:05.120
we're causing to the community
and to the environment

00:11:05.120 --> 00:11:08.290
around the home, but actually
restoring the environment

00:11:08.290 --> 00:11:09.790
around the home,
and actually seeing

00:11:09.790 --> 00:11:11.748
what we can do to make
this a restorative home.

00:11:11.748 --> 00:11:13.940
And we're on that
path towards it now.

00:11:13.940 --> 00:11:16.630
Because we have the ideal
as the indicator of success.

00:11:16.630 --> 00:11:18.950
And this the ideal.

00:11:18.950 --> 00:11:21.560
That's my daughter, Jane.

00:11:21.560 --> 00:11:23.930
She's four years old now.

00:11:23.930 --> 00:11:26.540
She's the first
generation that will never

00:11:26.540 --> 00:11:29.650
know what it's like to grow
up in a carbon polluting home.

00:11:29.650 --> 00:11:32.310
She has no idea.

00:11:32.310 --> 00:11:37.550
Because this is the home that
she's getting to grow up in.

00:11:37.550 --> 00:11:41.020
This is the house in 1913.

00:11:41.020 --> 00:11:43.860
This is Philip and
Elizabeth Gouse.

00:11:43.860 --> 00:11:48.760
We bought the house
from Gert in 2006.

00:11:48.760 --> 00:11:51.845
So we're really the second
family to own this house.

00:11:51.845 --> 00:11:52.720
This is the backyard.

00:11:52.720 --> 00:11:54.929
You can see the coal
underneath covered with soot,

00:11:54.929 --> 00:11:57.815
and some of the grape vines they
used later during Prohibition.

00:11:57.815 --> 00:11:59.055
And this is 7th Street.

00:11:59.055 --> 00:12:00.680
These are the hydrangeas
that are still

00:12:00.680 --> 00:12:02.650
on the side of our house.

00:12:02.650 --> 00:12:04.800
This is Grizzly Peak
Brewing Company,

00:12:04.800 --> 00:12:07.550
over at the corner of Washington
and [INAUDIBLE] Street.

00:12:07.550 --> 00:12:10.720
It was just shortly after
this photograph was taken,

00:12:10.720 --> 00:12:12.930
it became the
Philip Gouse Saloon.

00:12:12.930 --> 00:12:14.840
So he would walk
out the front door

00:12:14.840 --> 00:12:18.610
to serve beer to customers
over 100 years ago,

00:12:18.610 --> 00:12:21.880
to the same place that we now
go to get beer and French fries.

00:12:21.880 --> 00:12:24.723
But what makes this photograph
unique, and the reason

00:12:24.723 --> 00:12:29.110
it was taken, was this was
the day where the Gouse

00:12:29.110 --> 00:12:32.227
family didn't have
to burn things

00:12:32.227 --> 00:12:33.560
themselves for their own energy.

00:12:33.560 --> 00:12:35.100
They could flip a
light switch, and they

00:12:35.100 --> 00:12:37.060
would get electricity
delivered to their house,

00:12:37.060 --> 00:12:39.476
with carbon burning somewhere
else that they no longer had

00:12:39.476 --> 00:12:40.127
to see.

00:12:40.127 --> 00:12:42.460
First time in human history
that this had ever happened,

00:12:42.460 --> 00:12:47.930
as soon as we started remotely
supplying electricity to homes.

00:12:47.930 --> 00:12:50.420
So Wendell Berry says,
when going back make sense,

00:12:50.420 --> 00:12:51.244
we move forward.

00:12:51.244 --> 00:12:52.785
So we really want
to take a look back

00:12:52.785 --> 00:12:55.900
at what was done
right back in the day.

00:12:55.900 --> 00:12:57.425
Now historic
preservationists love

00:12:57.425 --> 00:13:00.530
to say that old buildings are
the greenest buildings around.

00:13:00.530 --> 00:13:01.850
And there's some truth to that.

00:13:01.850 --> 00:13:04.340
They certainly did recognize
the patterns of nature.

00:13:04.340 --> 00:13:06.210
You could look at our backyard.

00:13:06.210 --> 00:13:07.955
Again, this is 1915.

00:13:07.955 --> 00:13:10.530
That's Robert again
in our backyard.

00:13:10.530 --> 00:13:13.080
And you can see
some of the things

00:13:13.080 --> 00:13:16.270
where this house was
net zero water when

00:13:16.270 --> 00:13:18.180
the Gouses' lived in it.

00:13:18.180 --> 00:13:20.920
This is the cistern
cap over here.

00:13:20.920 --> 00:13:23.600
Over to the far right, you
could see the well water,

00:13:23.600 --> 00:13:25.350
where they'd bring in
a little fresh water

00:13:25.350 --> 00:13:27.641
that they needed for the
house, to fill up the bath tub

00:13:27.641 --> 00:13:28.890
or to cook with.

00:13:28.890 --> 00:13:30.530
All the rain water
fell off of the roof

00:13:30.530 --> 00:13:33.426
into the cistern that was used
for the gardens, the vegetable

00:13:33.426 --> 00:13:34.425
gardens in the backyard.

00:13:34.425 --> 00:13:36.140
So a good percentage
of their food,

00:13:36.140 --> 00:13:39.745
up until the 1940's, about
40% of produce in America

00:13:39.745 --> 00:13:42.760
was grown in people's yards.

00:13:42.760 --> 00:13:44.640
Back there, there
were chicken coops.

00:13:44.640 --> 00:13:48.360
In the 1950's, they started
making chickens illegal.

00:13:48.360 --> 00:13:49.446
They're legal again now.

00:13:49.446 --> 00:13:51.355
We have a few in our backyard.

00:13:51.355 --> 00:13:53.500
Then there was a dog
house back there for Fido.

00:13:53.500 --> 00:13:55.864
Now Fido's job was
to guard the chickens

00:13:55.864 --> 00:13:57.280
from the foxes and
things that ran

00:13:57.280 --> 00:13:58.980
around the Old West
Side of Ann Arbor.

00:13:58.980 --> 00:14:00.513
The foxes are long gone.

00:14:00.513 --> 00:14:04.550
But they did have the
composting toilet, also known

00:14:04.550 --> 00:14:05.960
as the outhouse.

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:08.370
So a couple of these things
are wonderful to go back to.

00:14:08.370 --> 00:14:12.287
Natural ventilation, harvesting
food from our own property,

00:14:12.287 --> 00:14:13.870
capturing our water,
things like that.

00:14:13.870 --> 00:14:15.740
And certainly,
composting toilets.

00:14:15.740 --> 00:14:18.070
But that's probably
not the best design.

00:14:18.070 --> 00:14:21.077
I think we could probably
do better than that.

00:14:21.077 --> 00:14:22.660
But that these
households were perfect

00:14:22.660 --> 00:14:25.370
is really the myth
of the noble house.

00:14:25.370 --> 00:14:30.080
Because the Gouses' were burning
about 1,200 pounds of coal

00:14:30.080 --> 00:14:33.280
to cook and heat with
every single month.

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:36.190
That's about 100
pounds of ash alone.

00:14:36.190 --> 00:14:40.263
That's not a way we're going to
go back to heating or cooking.

00:14:43.910 --> 00:14:47.715
Our streams and our rivers
were turned into sewers.

00:14:47.715 --> 00:14:50.090
There were so polluted with
chemicals and everything else

00:14:50.090 --> 00:14:51.673
from all the industrial
processes that

00:14:51.673 --> 00:14:53.835
were going in in Ann
Arbor, heavy metal, sewage,

00:14:53.835 --> 00:14:56.355
you name it, was going
straight into the creeks,

00:14:56.355 --> 00:14:58.560
that in the 1930's
we decided, hey

00:14:58.560 --> 00:15:00.950
we have the engineering
capability of just turning

00:15:00.950 --> 00:15:03.930
these natural services
into actual sewers.

00:15:03.930 --> 00:15:06.085
And now they're buried
in a concrete pipe.

00:15:06.085 --> 00:15:08.910
And throughout Ann Arbor, just
about every one of us every day

00:15:08.910 --> 00:15:10.962
walks across one
of these creeks,

00:15:10.962 --> 00:15:12.795
without ever knowing
that it's ever existed.

00:15:12.795 --> 00:15:15.280
One of them runs right
next door to our house.

00:15:15.280 --> 00:15:18.570
This is the Allen Creek, as
it goes underneath Washington

00:15:18.570 --> 00:15:21.930
Street, right by the YMCA.

00:15:21.930 --> 00:15:25.350
It's buried under a pipe.

00:15:25.350 --> 00:15:29.230
Before the Gouses' in the
1700's, early 1800 's,

00:15:29.230 --> 00:15:34.510
the primary fuel for cooking
and heating was wood.

00:15:34.510 --> 00:15:36.607
Now humans are the
only species on earth

00:15:36.607 --> 00:15:38.690
that have ever burned
anything for our own comfort

00:15:38.690 --> 00:15:41.170
and survival.

00:15:41.170 --> 00:15:43.150
So wood was plentiful.

00:15:43.150 --> 00:15:46.720
In 1799, they
wrote that Michigan

00:15:46.720 --> 00:15:50.660
had inexhaustible hard pine
forests, inexhaustible.

00:15:50.660 --> 00:15:52.706
No way you could
possibly use it all.

00:15:52.706 --> 00:15:55.830
The canopy of the trees
was so thick and dense,

00:15:55.830 --> 00:15:58.180
they said a squirrel could
hop across the canopy

00:15:58.180 --> 00:16:01.485
from the Upper Peninsula of
Michigan all the way down

00:16:01.485 --> 00:16:03.895
to Northern Florida without
ever touching the ground.

00:16:03.895 --> 00:16:06.394
That's how thick the forests
of the East Coast of the United

00:16:06.394 --> 00:16:07.618
States were.

00:16:07.618 --> 00:16:14.270
But by 1890, this is
about how much wood

00:16:14.270 --> 00:16:18.340
each house was burning at the
time, 15 to 20 cord of wood.

00:16:18.340 --> 00:16:22.112
So to give you an idea, that's
4 feet wide, 16 feet high,

00:16:22.112 --> 00:16:24.320
up to the top of these
ceilings, and the entire width

00:16:24.320 --> 00:16:28.190
of this hall here.

00:16:28.190 --> 00:16:29.920
Every single home
was burning that,

00:16:29.920 --> 00:16:31.880
just to cook and heat with.

00:16:31.880 --> 00:16:36.960
So by 1890, this was
Hermanville, Michigan.

00:16:36.960 --> 00:16:40.430
We had exhausted 95% of
all of the forest cover

00:16:40.430 --> 00:16:43.575
in the state of Michigan
in less than 100 years.

00:16:46.044 --> 00:16:47.835
That was before the
population of the world

00:16:47.835 --> 00:16:49.590
had hit 1 billion people.

00:16:49.590 --> 00:16:55.790
So we can't go back to--
I was in a farmer's market

00:16:55.790 --> 00:16:57.470
and somebody was selling kale.

00:16:57.470 --> 00:16:59.675
And this guy with dreadlocks
said to me, hey, well,

00:16:59.675 --> 00:17:01.150
we can just go back
to living in yurts.

00:17:01.150 --> 00:17:02.691
And I'm like, well,
how are you going

00:17:02.691 --> 00:17:05.750
to heat 130 million
yurts in the US?

00:17:05.750 --> 00:17:08.319
That's not really a
sustainable solution either.

00:17:08.319 --> 00:17:10.260
We can do better than that.

00:17:10.260 --> 00:17:11.010
Lighting.

00:17:11.010 --> 00:17:14.310
Every neighborhood,
every city had a place

00:17:14.310 --> 00:17:19.329
where you could in and buy any
kind of liquid that burned,

00:17:19.329 --> 00:17:19.829
really.

00:17:19.829 --> 00:17:23.874
You had lard oil, camphor,
kerosene, whale oil.

00:17:23.874 --> 00:17:27.939
If it was liquid and it
burned, they sold it.

00:17:27.939 --> 00:17:31.530
And this is how
we lit our homes.

00:17:31.530 --> 00:17:34.055
And I think it's
coming up pretty soon,

00:17:34.055 --> 00:17:36.160
they call it Earth Hour.

00:17:36.160 --> 00:17:37.980
Earth Hour is where
around the globe,

00:17:37.980 --> 00:17:39.510
we want to bring awareness
to the amount of electricity

00:17:39.510 --> 00:17:40.010
we use.

00:17:40.010 --> 00:17:42.218
And so they have everyone
just turn off their lights.

00:17:42.218 --> 00:17:44.460
They turn off the lights
that illuminate the Eiffel

00:17:44.460 --> 00:17:49.720
Tower, the Empire State
Building in New York.

00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:52.080
And everyone gets together
and has these really intimate

00:17:52.080 --> 00:17:52.580
meals.

00:17:52.580 --> 00:17:55.990
We all light
candles to put focus

00:17:55.990 --> 00:17:58.900
on the attention of how
much energy we're using.

00:17:58.900 --> 00:18:01.430
So some enterprising
young graduate student

00:18:01.430 --> 00:18:05.325
decided, well, how much CO2
comes out of a paraffin candle?

00:18:05.325 --> 00:18:09.570
Can we go back away from the
light bulb to the paraffin

00:18:09.570 --> 00:18:11.600
candle to light
our way at night ?

00:18:11.600 --> 00:18:14.310
And he figured out that
the paraffin candle

00:18:14.310 --> 00:18:17.390
uses 10 times the amount of CO2
of an incandescent light bulb

00:18:17.390 --> 00:18:19.280
per lumen.

00:18:19.280 --> 00:18:22.230
So we're not going
back to that, either.

00:18:22.230 --> 00:18:25.070
And this is what
our electric lights

00:18:25.070 --> 00:18:29.019
look like at night from space.

00:18:29.019 --> 00:18:31.310
Somebody said once, it looks
like the planet's on fire.

00:18:31.310 --> 00:18:32.540
And in a way, it is.

00:18:32.540 --> 00:18:35.081
Because we're actually digging
up these 100 millions of years

00:18:35.081 --> 00:18:40.500
of stored solar energy and
burning them for electricity,

00:18:40.500 --> 00:18:43.150
and setting all the particulate
matter and all that carbon

00:18:43.150 --> 00:18:45.358
that was stored in the ground
up into the atmosphere.

00:18:45.358 --> 00:18:47.340
And that number rises
every single day.

00:18:47.340 --> 00:18:48.340
So here's the challenge.

00:18:48.340 --> 00:18:53.450
We've got 130 million existing
homes in America already here.

00:18:53.450 --> 00:18:57.030
So California has said, look,
if we're going to do this,

00:18:57.030 --> 00:19:01.040
then all new homes from now on,
starting about the 2020 Energy

00:19:01.040 --> 00:19:03.550
Code, they have to
be net zero energy.

00:19:03.550 --> 00:19:05.334
And that's incredibly ambitious.

00:19:05.334 --> 00:19:06.125
And it's necessary.

00:19:06.125 --> 00:19:09.490
And it's a wonderful
thing they're doing.

00:19:09.490 --> 00:19:11.320
But if you really
think about it,

00:19:11.320 --> 00:19:14.630
if all new homes and all new
buildings are net zero energy.

00:19:14.630 --> 00:19:17.996
They don't emit a single
bit of carbon pollution

00:19:17.996 --> 00:19:20.770
for their entire life,
starting this afternoon,

00:19:20.770 --> 00:19:23.300
everything new, zero emissions.

00:19:23.300 --> 00:19:28.652
How much does that lower
our current carbon output?

00:19:28.652 --> 00:19:31.070
And the answer is zero.

00:19:34.390 --> 00:19:38.950
We have to do something with
the existing building stock.

00:19:38.950 --> 00:19:41.070
So is that really possible?

00:19:41.070 --> 00:19:45.164
Well, Amory Lovins says if it
exists, it must be possible.

00:19:45.164 --> 00:19:46.455
So let me show you what exists.

00:19:49.470 --> 00:19:51.100
These are the numbers
from our house.

00:19:51.100 --> 00:19:52.730
The slide's a
little bit outdated.

00:19:52.730 --> 00:19:56.700
This is from October,
2011 through 2012.

00:19:56.700 --> 00:20:00.240
So this a year's worth of
energy data for our house.

00:20:00.240 --> 00:20:02.980
On the roof of our house,
we produce 95 kilowatt hours

00:20:02.980 --> 00:20:04.610
of solar.

00:20:04.610 --> 00:20:08.750
We used about 7,500 kilowatts,
and we put 2,000 kilowatts back

00:20:08.750 --> 00:20:12.266
onto the grid, that
we weren't even using.

00:20:12.266 --> 00:20:13.682
This is what a
typical energy bill

00:20:13.682 --> 00:20:17.982
looks like in our house, minus
the $8 a month, give or take.

00:20:17.982 --> 00:20:19.232
Sometimes it's more than that.

00:20:19.232 --> 00:20:21.570
Sometimes it's in the 100's,
sometimes a little bit less

00:20:21.570 --> 00:20:22.070
than that.

00:20:22.070 --> 00:20:25.390
So we did some math, and we
figured that over 30 years,

00:20:25.390 --> 00:20:27.980
the life of our mortgage--
people go into the house,

00:20:27.980 --> 00:20:30.230
they know exactly how much
taxes they're going to pay,

00:20:30.230 --> 00:20:32.310
they know how much the
mortgage is going to be.

00:20:32.310 --> 00:20:33.400
And I'll even give
you a chart when

00:20:33.400 --> 00:20:35.525
you get your loan, what
are you going to spend over

00:20:35.525 --> 00:20:37.100
30 years with all
of that interest.

00:20:37.100 --> 00:20:39.016
But nobody says, what
am I going to spend over

00:20:39.016 --> 00:20:42.370
30 years to run this house?

00:20:42.370 --> 00:20:46.835
And this is the number that we
came up with, $283,000 of shift

00:20:46.835 --> 00:20:49.940
in energy costs for
us over 30 years.

00:20:49.940 --> 00:20:53.010
Now in fairness, that's
at 7% energy inflation.

00:20:53.010 --> 00:20:56.101
And the coal industry say, well,
it's only going to be 4.3%.

00:20:56.101 --> 00:20:57.600
So if we split the
difference, we're

00:20:57.600 --> 00:21:01.800
still talking about $234,000
energy swing for us.

00:21:01.800 --> 00:21:07.200
So net zero energy has gotten
the financial thumbs up.

00:21:07.200 --> 00:21:08.745
But the coal industry is right.

00:21:08.745 --> 00:21:11.960
And they'll say, well, look,
that's not fair to say 7%,

00:21:11.960 --> 00:21:15.000
because we have no idea
what the price of energy

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:16.910
is going to be
like in the future.

00:21:16.910 --> 00:21:20.370
And that's exactly the point.

00:21:20.370 --> 00:21:25.080
There's no commodity trader
on the planet, not the best

00:21:25.080 --> 00:21:28.620
ones out there, that will
know that in 20 minutes

00:21:28.620 --> 00:21:32.600
at the close of the
Commodity Exchange today,

00:21:32.600 --> 00:21:36.975
how much the raw cost of coal
or petroleum or natural gas

00:21:36.975 --> 00:21:37.600
is going to be.

00:21:37.600 --> 00:21:40.540
They don't know it today,
tomorrow, five days from now.

00:21:40.540 --> 00:21:41.682
No idea.

00:21:41.682 --> 00:21:43.870
They might get an
approximation, but they'll never

00:21:43.870 --> 00:21:45.387
get the number right.

00:21:45.387 --> 00:21:47.220
But any 5-year-old can
tell you exactly what

00:21:47.220 --> 00:21:49.950
the raw cost of solar
energy or wind energy

00:21:49.950 --> 00:21:53.436
is going to be 10,000
years from now.

00:21:53.436 --> 00:21:55.060
The only difference
in cost is the cost

00:21:55.060 --> 00:21:57.390
of building the power plant.

00:21:57.390 --> 00:21:59.462
So here's how you do it.

00:21:59.462 --> 00:22:00.670
It's a pretty simple formula.

00:22:00.670 --> 00:22:02.211
You lose less, you
use less, and then

00:22:02.211 --> 00:22:03.920
you produce all the
energy that you need.

00:22:03.920 --> 00:22:06.377
And what you do is you really
try to optimize your comfort.

00:22:06.377 --> 00:22:08.690
Because when we first moved
in, and people started

00:22:08.690 --> 00:22:11.960
writing about our house
and the work we were doing,

00:22:11.960 --> 00:22:13.800
everyone immediately
assumed, clearly,

00:22:13.800 --> 00:22:16.090
they're hippies bathing
in their pasta water.

00:22:16.090 --> 00:22:18.658
This is-- [LAUGHTER]

00:22:18.658 --> 00:22:21.937
But as it turns out, we invite
over 1,000 people a year

00:22:21.937 --> 00:22:23.020
to come through our house.

00:22:23.020 --> 00:22:24.580
And we show them, we have
all the same appliances

00:22:24.580 --> 00:22:25.820
that everybody else has.

00:22:28.670 --> 00:22:30.520
The difference is
that they're always

00:22:30.520 --> 00:22:33.290
the most efficient appliances,
and we control them.

00:22:33.290 --> 00:22:35.880
So right now, our
home, I can tell you,

00:22:35.880 --> 00:22:38.322
without even looking--
and I have a little app

00:22:38.322 --> 00:22:40.734
for that-- exactly how
much energy we're using.

00:22:40.734 --> 00:22:43.540
And it's probably less
than 200 watts right now,

00:22:43.540 --> 00:22:45.840
less than a few of these
light bulbs in this room.

00:22:45.840 --> 00:22:47.977
Our entire house is
operating off of that right

00:22:47.977 --> 00:22:49.130
now, because nobody's home.

00:22:52.660 --> 00:22:54.660
That little thing over
there on the corner, that

00:22:54.660 --> 00:22:57.660
is the one old thing
that we still have.

00:22:57.660 --> 00:23:01.270
That was my clock radio that I
bought in law school in 1992.

00:23:01.270 --> 00:23:03.580
And just plugging that in,
doing a little math on it,

00:23:03.580 --> 00:23:05.380
I realized that actually
uses more energy

00:23:05.380 --> 00:23:08.000
throughout the year than the
TV set up on the upper right

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:08.540
corner.

00:23:08.540 --> 00:23:09.940
So it's not about
sacrificing, saying

