MATT GROCOFF: Yeah.

00:36:55.720 --> 00:36:57.210
Well, one of the things
they've done in Germany

00:36:57.210 --> 00:36:59.185
is that they really
democratized the grid.

00:36:59.185 --> 00:37:01.230
As free as we are
in this country,

00:37:01.230 --> 00:37:04.560
we don't get to
own our own energy.

00:37:04.560 --> 00:37:06.367
Because a century
ago, we decided

00:37:06.367 --> 00:37:08.075
that whoever was going
to make that grid,

00:37:08.075 --> 00:37:09.540
it was going to be
at great expense.

00:37:09.540 --> 00:37:11.706
So just like the railroads,
we gave them monopolies.

00:37:11.706 --> 00:37:13.820
And we've been
trying to figure out

00:37:13.820 --> 00:37:15.720
how to manage that ever since.

00:37:15.720 --> 00:37:19.870
So we have this really
old, outdated grid system

00:37:19.870 --> 00:37:22.420
of electricity that's
like a Christmas tree.

00:37:22.420 --> 00:37:25.070
If one part goes out, you lose
the entire eastern seaboard,

00:37:25.070 --> 00:37:27.375
like we did a few years ago.

00:37:27.375 --> 00:37:31.000
If Google wanted to use
all of this roof space

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:33.980
and sell the energy to
some of the other floors

00:37:33.980 --> 00:37:37.810
or the building next door, you
wouldn't be allowed to do that.

00:37:37.810 --> 00:37:41.105
So the utility company
owns the energy.

00:37:41.105 --> 00:37:44.200
If you put excess
onto it, they get it.

00:37:44.200 --> 00:37:48.296
We were lucky enough to get into
a program that was around just

00:37:48.296 --> 00:37:50.620
