00:43:26.760 --> 00:43:29.310
So that's the most significant
thing we've gotten was

00:43:29.310 --> 00:43:32.007
we were rewarded for
restoring a historic house.

00:43:32.007 --> 00:43:33.840
I could do a whole hour
lecture on that one,

00:43:33.840 --> 00:43:36.672
though, because we almost
didn't get it, because of some--

00:43:38.910 --> 00:43:41.160
AUDIENCE: Could I ask somewhat
of a follow-up question

00:43:41.160 --> 00:43:41.660
to that?

00:43:41.660 --> 00:43:45.460
It seems like, as you
said, the short-term costs

00:43:45.460 --> 00:43:49.316
are a significant barrier to
something that is obviously

00:43:49.316 --> 00:43:52.540
going to pay for itself
over the long run.

00:43:55.140 --> 00:43:58.830
What are your thoughts on
models that you think work well.

00:43:58.830 --> 00:44:01.904
And I know there's been a lot
of [INAUDIBLE] subsidies from

00:44:01.904 --> 00:44:05.460
solar companies
that are no longer--

00:44:05.460 --> 00:44:09.066
I'm trying to think about, it
seems like there could be some

00:44:09.066 --> 00:44:11.850
sort of way that somebody who
had a lot of capital could make

00:44:11.850 --> 00:44:16.555
this a very profitable
program to just subsidize--

00:44:16.555 --> 00:44:17.680
MATT GROCOFF: And they are.

00:44:17.680 --> 00:44:19.221
There are solar
leasing programs that

00:44:19.221 --> 00:44:21.990
are very successful in
other states, where they

00:44:21.990 --> 00:44:25.200
own the solar panels, and
they're leasing you the panel.

00:44:25.200 --> 00:44:27.232
So that way they get
around who owns the energy.

00:44:27.232 --> 00:44:28.690
They're not selling
you the energy,

00:44:28.690 --> 00:44:30.235
they're selling me
the power plant.

00:44:30.235 --> 00:44:32.110
They're not even selling
you the power plant,

00:44:32.110 --> 00:44:33.906
they own the power
plant on your roof.

00:44:33.906 --> 00:44:35.530
You lease it back from them.

00:44:35.530 --> 00:44:37.780
And your payments
each month are lower

00:44:37.780 --> 00:44:40.160
than what you would be paying
if you bought electricity

00:44:40.160 --> 00:44:42.220
from the utility company.

00:44:42.220 --> 00:44:45.160
So that's one model.

00:44:45.160 --> 00:44:47.870
But all of this really has
to change dramatically.

00:44:47.870 --> 00:44:50.120
We can't just keep
throwing money

00:44:50.120 --> 00:44:52.700
at this company or that
company and hoping it works.

00:44:52.700 --> 00:44:55.300
We really have to put a
price-- the reason solar is

00:44:55.300 --> 00:44:58.480
at a disadvantage is because
the other forms of fossil fuels

00:44:58.480 --> 00:45:00.950
are artificially
cheap, because we

00:45:00.950 --> 00:45:03.070
don't pay for the cost of that.

00:45:03.070 --> 00:45:05.945
You don't see in the cost of oil
spills in the Kalamazoo River

00:45:05.945 --> 00:45:07.880
or in the Gulf of Mexico.

00:45:07.880 --> 00:45:10.265
You don't see the cost of
the invisible carbon dioxide

00:45:10.265 --> 00:45:13.900
and methane and everything else
that goes up to the atmosphere.

00:45:13.900 --> 00:45:15.000
Nobody pays that.

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:17.170
That's just the tragedy
of the [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:17.170 --> 00:45:19.600
So if we actually
calculate those costs

00:45:19.600 --> 00:45:23.190
and see what they
really are, then

00:45:23.190 --> 00:45:29.320
all of a sudden how we create
our energy really changes.

00:45:29.320 --> 00:45:31.225
And so that's why
Germany is, really, I

00:45:31.225 --> 00:45:33.920
think, the best model
we've got so far for it.

00:45:33.920 --> 00:45:35.490
And they're on target.

00:45:35.490 --> 00:45:37.300
They'll do it by 2030.

00:45:37.300 --> 00:45:41.340
And we could all do it, if
we have the political will.

00:45:41.340 --> 00:45:41.940
Anybody else?

00:45:44.940 --> 00:45:45.840
All right.

00:45:45.840 --> 00:45:46.740
Thanks, y'all.

